Author-Name:    Diamond, Douglas W
Title:   Monitoring and Reputation: The Choice between Bank Loans and Directly Placed Debt. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 689-721
Issue: 4
Volume: 99
Year: 1991
Month:  August 
Abstract:
  This paper determines when a debt contract will be monitored by lenders.
 This is the choice between borrowing directly (issuing a bond, without
 monitoring) and borrowing through a bank that monitors to alleviate moral
 hazard. This provides a theory of bank loan demand and of the role of
 monitoring in circumstances in which reputation effects are important. A
 key result is that borrowers with credit ratings toward the middle of the
 spectrum rely on bank loans, and in periods of high interest rates or low
 future profitability, higher-rated borrowers choose to borrow from banks.  Copyright 1991 by University of Chicago Press.
