Author-Name:    Chaloupka, Frank
Title:   Rational Addictive Behavior and Cigarette Smoking. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 722-42
Issue: 4
Volume: 99
Year: 1991
Month:  August 
Abstract:
  Cigarette demand equations accounting for tolerance, reinforcement, and
 withdrawal are derived using the Becker-Murphy model of rational addiction
 and are estimated using data from the second National Health and Nutrition
 Examination Survey. Estimates imply that smoking is addictive, individuals
 are not myopic, and price increases would reduce demand. Implications
 concerning time preference and addiction are tested by estimating the
 demand separately for samples based on age and education. Less educated
 (younger) individuals are found to behave more myopically than more
 educated (older) individuals, whereas more addicted (myopic) individuals
 are found to respond more to price, in the long run, than less addicted
 (myopic) individuals.  Copyright 1991 by University of Chicago Press.
