Author-Name:    Parsons, Donald O
Title:   Self-Screening in Targeted Public Transfer Programs. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 859-76
Issue: 4
Volume: 99
Year: 1991
Month:  August 
Abstract:
  The self-screening properties of initial eligibility determination, a
 mechanism often under the control of the administrators of targeted
 transfer programs, are derived and the use of this mechanism in the social
 security disability insurance system is explored empirically. An increase
 in the rigor of initial eligibility screening may discourage potential
 applicants because they are unaware of appeal prospects and because the
 eligibility decision delay is lengthened, as denied applicants are forced
 to appeal their claims. In the disability program, a 10 percent increase
 in the initial denial rate induces a 4 percent decrease in applications.
 Self-selection is nonperverse.  Copyright 1991 by University of Chicago Press.
