Author-Name:    Smith, Vernon L
Title:   Rational Choice: The Contrast between Economics and Psychology. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 877-97
Issue: 4
Volume: 99
Year: 1991
Month:  August 
Abstract:
  Rational Choice--the published record of a conference on economics and
 psychology--frames the issues as a contest between economic theory and the
 falsifying evidence from psychology. According to a third perspective,
 that of experimental economics, most standard theory provides a correct
 first approximation in predicting motivated behavior in laboratory
 experimental markets, but the theory is incomplete, particularly in
 articulating convergence processes in time and in ignoring decision cost.
 This view has roots in the work of Herbert Simon and Signey Siegel, but it
 is not plainly represented in contemporary research in economic
 psychology.  Copyright 1991 by University of Chicago Press.
